y:CA Osasuna players]]\n[[Category:Deportivo Alav\u00e9s players]]\n[[Category:Danish Superliga players]]\n[[Category:Odense Boldklub players]]\n[[Category:Indian Super League players]]\n[[Category:FC Pune City players]]\n[[Category:Mumbai City FC players]]\n[[Category:Swiss Super League players]]\n[[Category:Grasshopper Club Z\u00fcrich players]]\n[[Category:A-League players]]\n[[Category:Perth Glory FC players]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Kitchee SC players]]\n[[Category:Uruguayan Primera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Pe\u00f1arol players]]\n[[Category:Hungary under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Hungary international footballers]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in France]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in India]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in Australia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Uruguay]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate sportspeople in France]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate sportspeople in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate sportspeople in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate sportspeople in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate sportspeople in India]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate sportspeople in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate sportspeople in Australia]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate sportspeople in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate sportspeople in Uruguay]]\n", "text_old": "{{Eastern name order|Vad\u00f3cz Kriszti\u00e1n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Kriszti\u00e1n Vad\u00f3cz\n| image = Kriszti\u00e1n Vad\u00f3cz.jpg\n| image_size = 250\n| caption = Vad\u00f3cz playing with [[Kitchee SC|Kitchee]] in 2017\n| fullname =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1985|5|30|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Budapest]], Hungary\n| height = {{convert|1.88|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| position = [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Pe\u00f1arol]]\n| clubnumber = 28\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[Budapest Honv\u00e9d FC|Honv\u00e9d]]\n| years1 = 2002\u20132005 | clubs1 = [[Budapest Honv\u00e9d FC|Honv\u00e9d]] | caps1 = 72 | goals1 = 7\n| years2 = 2005\u20132007 | clubs2 = [[AJ Auxerre|Auxerre B]] | caps2 = 32 | goals2 = 2\n| years3 = 2007 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] (loan) | caps3 = 11 | goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2007\u20132008 | clubs4 = [[N.E.C. (football club)|NEC]] | caps4 = 28 | goals4 = 2\n| years5 = 2008\u20132011 | clubs5 = [[CA Osasuna|Osasuna]] | caps5 = 71 | goals5 = 9\n| years6 = 2011\u20132012 | clubs6 = [[N.E.C. (football club)|NEC]] | caps6 = 29 | goals6 = 1\n| years7 = 2012\u20132014 | clubs7 = [[Odense Boldklub|Odense]] | caps7 = 36 | goals7 = 9\n| years8 = 2014 | clubs8 = [[FC Pune City|Pune City]] | caps8 = 6 | goals8 = 0\n| years9 = 2015 | clubs9 = [[Grasshopper Club Z\u00fcrich|Grasshoppers]] | caps9 = 15 | goals9 = 2\n| years10 = 2015\u20132016 | clubs10 = [[Deportivo Alav\u00e9s|Alav\u00e9s]] | caps10 = 3 | goals10 = 0\n| years11 = 2016 | clubs11 = [[Perth Glory FC|Perth Glory]] | caps11 = 11 | goals11 = 1\n| years12 = 2016 | clubs12 = [[Mumbai City FC|Mumbai City]] | caps12 = 14 | goals12 = 3\n| years13 = 2017\u20132018 | clubs13 = [[Kitchee SC|Kitchee]] | caps13 = 27 | goals13 = 10 \n| years14 = 2018 | clubs14 = [[Budapest Honv\u00e9d FC|Honv\u00e9d]] | caps14 = 6 | goals14 = 0 \n| years15 = 2018\u20132019 | clubs15 = [[Kitchee SC|Kitchee]] | caps15 = 13 | goals15 = 3\n| years16 = 2019 | clubs16 = [[Budapest Honv\u00e9d FC|Honv\u00e9d]] | caps16 = 11 | goals16 = 0\n| years17 = 2020\u2013 | clubs17 = [[Pe\u00f1arol]] | caps17 = 1 | goals17 = 0\n| totalcaps = | totalgoals = \n| nationalyears1 = 2004\u20132006 | nationalteam1 = [[Hungary national under-21 football team|Hungary U21]] | nationalcaps1 = 3 | nationalgoals1 = 0 \n| nationalyears2 = 2004\u2013 | nationalteam2 = [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] | nationalcaps2 = 42 | nationalgoals2 = 2\n| club-update = 16 February 2020\n| nationalteam-update = 10 June 2018\n}}\n\n'''Kriszti\u00e1n Vad\u00f3cz''' ({{IPA-hu|\u02c8kristia\u02d0n \u02c8v\u0252do\u02d0t\u0361s|lang}}; born 30 May 1985) is a [[Hungary|Hungarian]] professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for Uruguayan club [[Pe\u00f1arol]] as a [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|central midfielder]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Early years===\nBorn in [[Budapest]], Vad\u00f3cz made his professional debuts aged 17, with hometown's [[Budapest Honv\u00e9d FC]], and caught the eye of [[Ligue 1]] club [[AJ Auxerre]] in summer 2005. However, he managed no first-team appearances in a three-year spell, finishing his last on loan to [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] in [[Scotland]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/m/motherwell/6315479.stm Hungarian agrees Well loan deal]; [[BBC Sport]], 31 January 2007</ref>\n\nIn June 2007, Vad\u00f3cz was finally released by the French, joining [[N.E.C. (football club)|NEC Nijmegen]]. During [[2007\u201308 Eredivisie|his only season]] in the [[Eredivisie]], he was an essential midfield element for a team that finished a comfortable eighth.\n\n===Osasuna===\nSubsequently, Vad\u00f3cz penned a four-year contract with [[CA Osasuna]].<ref>[https://www.sport.es/es/noticias/futbol/osasuna-ficha-al-medio-hungaro-krisztian-vadocz-5824799 Osasuna ficha al medio h\u00fangaro Krisztian Vadocz (Osasuna sign Hungarian midfielder Kristian Vadocz)]; [[Sport (Spanish newspaper)|Sport]], 11 August 2008 (in Spanish)</ref> Never an undisputed starter in [[2008\u201309 La Liga|his first season]] in [[La Liga]] he did score some important goals, against [[UD Almer\u00eda]] (3\u20131, after only playing one minute)<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/252827?cc=5739 Osasuna 3\u20131 Almeria]; [[ESPN FC|ESPN Soccernet]], 23 November 2008</ref> and at [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] (4\u20132).<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/253069?cc=5739 Atl\u00e9tico Madrid 2\u20134 Osasuna]; ESPN Soccernet, 5 April 2009</ref>\n\nIn the [[2009\u201310 La Liga|2009\u201310 campaign]], Vad\u00f3cz appeared in exactly the same number of matches for the [[Navarre]]se, again mainly [[Substitute (association football)|from the bench]]. On 11 April 2010, he netted from 35 yards to help his team to a 2\u20130 home win against [[Real Zaragoza]].<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/275683?cc=5739 Osasuna prove too strong for Zaragoza]; ESPN Soccernet, 11 April 2010</ref>\n\n===Late career===\nVad\u00f3cz was released by Osasuna in the last day of the 2011 summer [[transfer window]], immediately signing with former side NEC. On 6 September 2012 he changed clubs and countries again, joining [[Odense Boldklub]] in the [[Danish Superliga]].<ref>[http://www.ob.dk/artikel/krisztin-vadcz-praesenteret-i-ob.aspx Kriszti\u00e1n Vad\u00f3cz pr\u00e6senteret i OB (Kriszti\u00e1n Vad\u00f3cz presented at OB)]; Odense Boldklub, 6 September 2012 (in Danish)</ref>\n\nOn 14 November 2014, Vad\u00f3cz moved to the [[Indian Super League]] with [[FC Pune City]], as an injury replacement to [[John Goossens]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/sports/hungarian-krisztian-vadocz-replaces-injured-john-goossens-fc-pune-city-1803675.html|title=Hungarian Krisztian Vadocz replaces injured John Goossens at FC Pune City|publisher=[[Firstpost]]|date=14 November 2014|accessdate=14 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportskeeda.com/football/hungarian-vadocz-replaces-john-goossens-at-fc-pune-city|title=Former Osasuna midfielder Krisztian Vadocz joins FC Pune City replacing John Goossens|publisher=[[Sportskeeda]]|date=14 November 2014|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> On 16 February of the following year, he was signed by [[Grasshopper Club Z\u00fcrich]] from the [[Swiss Super League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gcz.ch/news/gc-news/news/gc-verpflichtet-mittelfeldspieler-krisztian-vadocz/3649a7756a36beb455224ca4f11989a0/|title=GC verpflichtet mittelfeldspieler Krisztian Vadocz|trans-title=GC acquire midfielder Krisztian Vadocz|publisher=Grasshopper CZ|language=de|date=16 February 2015|accessdate=16 February 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20150217020632/http://www.gcz.ch/news/gc-news/news/gc-verpflichtet-mittelfeldspieler-krisztian-vadocz/3649a7756a36beb455224ca4f11989a0/|archivedate=17 February 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nemzetisport.hu/legiosok/grasshoppers-vadocz-a-27-szeres-svajci-bajnoknal-folytatja-2395293|title=Sv\u00e1jc: Vad\u00f3cz a 27-szeres bajnokcsapatn\u00e1l folytatja|trans-title=Switzerland: Vad\u00f3cz moves to 27-time champions|publisher=[[Nemzeti Sport]]|language=hu|date=16 February 2015|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April 2015, Vad\u00f3cz scored twice against [[FC Sion]] to help to a 5\u20130 success at the [[Stade Tourbillon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gcz.ch/news/gc-news/news/50-sieg-im-tourbillon/f9dc0454a7fbdf2d52e55cb8bec34016/|title=5:0-Sieg im Tourbillon|trans-title=5:0-Win at Tourbillon|publisher=Grasshopper CZ|language=de|date=3 April 2015|accessdate=3 April 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20150404214445/http://www.gcz.ch/news/gc-news/news/50-sieg-im-tourbillon/f9dc0454a7fbdf2d52e55cb8bec34016/|archivedate=4 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 19 September he moved back to Spain, after agreeing to a one-year deal with [[Deportivo Alav\u00e9s]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deportivoalaves.com/el-deportivo-alaves-se-refuerza-con-el-centrocampista-hungaro-vadocz/|title=El Deportivo Alav\u00e9s se refuerza con el centrocampista h\u00fangaro Vad\u00f3cz|trans-title=Deportivo Alav\u00e9s bolster with Hungarian midfielder Vad\u00f3cz|publisher=Deportivo Alav\u00e9s|language=es|date=19 September 2015|accessdate=19 September 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150919223813/http://www.deportivoalaves.com/el-deportivo-alaves-se-refuerza-con-el-centrocampista-hungaro-vadocz/|archivedate=19 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 January 2016, after appearing rarely for the [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basques]], Vad\u00f3cz terminated his contract and joined [[Perth Glory FC]] on an injury-replacement contract.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2016/01/28/segunda/1453978866_610613.html|title=Vadocz rescind\u00f3 con el Alav\u00e9s y se va al Perth australiano|trans-title=Vadocz terminated with Alav\u00e9s and goes to Australia's Perth|publisher=[[Diario AS]]|language=es|date=28 January 2016|accessdate=28 January 2016}}</ref> At the end of [[2015\u201316 A-League|the season]], he was not offered a new deal and was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.a-league.com.au/article/perth-glory-reveal-squad-changes/1f2cuo6srjns2zkh1dk3i8qdx|title=Perth Glory reveal squad shake-up|publisher=[[Football Federation Australia]]|date=8 May 2016|accessdate=8 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nVad\u00f3cz signed for [[Mumbai City FC]] on 28 June 2016, thus returning to the Indian top division.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestatesman.com/news/sports/mumbai-fc-sign-krisztian-vadocz-gerson-vieira-for-isl-3/150905.html|title=Mumbai City FC sign Krisztian Vadocz, Gerson Vieira for ISL 3|publisher=[[The Statesman (India)|The Statesman]]|date=28 June 2016|accessdate=28 June 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011023401/http://www.thestatesman.com/news/sports/mumbai-fc-sign-krisztian-vadocz-gerson-vieira-for-isl-3/150905.html|archivedate=11 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Hong Kong Premier League]]'s [[Kitchee SC]] announced his signing for six months the following 11 January,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kitchee.com/news.php?id=505|title=\u5091\u5fd7\u518d\u7c3d\u5165\u570b\u5bb6\u968a\u6210\u54e1 \u92b3\u610f\u6311\u6230\u4e9e\u51a0\u76c3|trans-title=|publisher=Kitchee SC|language=zh|date=11 January 2017|accessdate=29 January 2017}}</ref> and on 8 June the 32-year-old renewed his contract with the latter until the end of the [[2017\u201318 Hong Kong Premier League|2017\u201318 campaign]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kitchee.com/news.php?id=557|title=\u5091\u5fd7\u8207\u524d\u5308\u7259\u5229\u570b\u8173\u83ef\u675c\u65af\u7e8c\u7d04\u4e00\u5e74|trans-title=|publisher=Kitchee SC|language=zh|date=8 June 2017|accessdate=18 June 2017}}</ref> where he won the Hong Kong Footballer of the Year, Players\u2019 Player of the Year, Most Favourite Player and Top Midfielder awards.<ref name=FOTY>{{cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/sport/hong-kong/article/2146646/emotional-krisztian-vadocz-scoops-four-awards-hong-kong-top|title=I\u2019m not crying, but it\u2019s emotional: Kitchee\u2019s Krisztian Vadocz scoops four at Hong Kong Top Footballer Awards|publisher=[[South China Morning Post]]|date=17 May 2018|accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nVad\u00f3cz returned to his native Hungary on 5 July 2018, agreeing to a one-year deal with Honv\u00e9d.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nemzetisport.hu/labdarugo_nb_i/honved-vadocz-krisztian-visszater-kispestre-hivatalos-2645545|title=Honv\u00e9d: Vad\u00f3cz Kriszti\u00e1n visszat\u00e9r Kispestre \u2013 hivatalos|trans-title=Honv\u00e9d: Kriszti\u00e1n Vad\u00f3cz returns to Kispest \u2013 official|publisher=Nemzeti Sport|language=hu|date=5 July 2018|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref> On 28 August, however, he terminated his contract by mutual consent because he opted to continue to play abroad.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nemzetisport.hu/labdarugo_nb_i/honved-vadocz-krisztian-maris-tavozik-a-klubtol-hivatalos-2655109|title=Honv\u00e9d: Vad\u00f3cz Kriszti\u00e1n m\u00e1ris t\u00e1vozik a klubt\u00f3l \u2013 hivatalos|trans-title=Honv\u00e9d: Kriszti\u00e1n Vad\u00f3cz leaves the club \u2013 official|publisher=Nemzeti Sport|language=hu|date=28 August 2018|accessdate=28 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nVad\u00f3cz returned to Kitchee on 17 October 2018, with head coach [[Chu Chi Kwong]] confirming that the player had signed a multi-year contract.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.mingpao.com/ins/instantnews/web_tc/article/20181017/s00006/1539762499344|title=\u6e2f\u8db3\u5148\u751f\u83ef\u675c\u65af\u56de\u6b78\u3000\u91cd\u8fd4\u5091\u5fd7\u52a9\u62f3\u722d\u4e0a\u524d\u5217|trans-title=Hong Kong Footballer of the Year Vad\u00f3cz returns to return to the top|publisher=[[Ming Pao]]|language=zh|date=17 October 2018|accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hk01.com/%E5%8D%B3%E6%99%82%E9%AB%94%E8%82%B2/248440/%E6%B8%AF%E8%B6%85%E8%81%AF-%E8%8F%AF%E6%9D%9C%E6%96%AF%E6%94%BE%E4%B8%8B%E5%8E%BB%E5%AD%A3%E5%85%89%E7%92%B0-%E5%88%9D%E8%A1%B7%E4%B9%8B%E5%BF%83%E7%9B%BC%E5%86%8D%E9%A0%98%E5%82%91%E5%BF%97%E8%A1%9D%E5%86%A0|title=\u83ef\u675c\u65af\u653e\u4e0b\u53bb\u5b63\u5149\u74b0\u3000\u521d\u8877\u4e4b\u5fc3\u76fc\u518d\u9818\u5091\u5fd7\u885d\u51a0|trans-title=|publisher=HK 01|last=Yuen|first=Chi Ho|language=zh|date=17 October 2018|accessdate=18 October 2018}}</ref> The following 27 August, he left.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hk01.com/%E5%8D%B3%E6%99%82%E9%AB%94%E8%82%B2/368635/%E6%B8%AF%E8%B6%85%E8%81%AF-%E5%82%91%E5%BF%97%E5%85%AC%E5%B8%83%E5%A4%96%E6%8F%B4%E5%90%8D%E5%96%AE-%E4%B8%AD%E5%A0%B4%E5%A4%A7%E5%B0%87%E9%9B%A2%E9%9A%8A-%E5%9C%96%E8%AA%AA%E8%8F%AF%E6%9D%9C%E6%96%AF%E5%9C%A8%E6%B8%AF%E7%94%9F%E6%B6%AF|title=\u5091\u5fd7\u516c\u5e03\u5916\u63f4\u540d\u55ae\u3000\u4e2d\u5834\u5927\u5c07\u96e2\u968a\u3000\u5716\u8aaa\u83ef\u675c\u65af\u5728\u6e2f\u751f\u6daf|trans-title=|publisher=HK 01|last=Yuen|first=Chi Ho|language=zh|date=27 August 2019|accessdate=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter a half year at Honv\u00e9d, Vad\u00f3cz joined [[Pe\u00f1arol]] of the [[Uruguayan Primera Divisi\u00f3n]] on 4 January 2020, where he was reunited with former Mumbai City teammate [[Diego Forl\u00e1n]] who acted as manager of the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.futbol.com.uy/Deportes/Penarol--Si-te-llama-Diego-Forlan-no-podes-decirle-que-no--dijo-Krisztian-Vadocz-uc740271|title=Pe\u00f1arol: \u201cSi te llama Diego Forl\u00e1n no pod\u00e9s decirle que no\u201d, dijo Krisztian Vad\u00f3cz|trans-title=Pe\u00f1arol: \u201cIf Diego Forl\u00e1n calls you you can't say no\u201d, said Krisztian Vad\u00f3cz|publisher=F\u00fatbol Uruguay|language=es|date=4 January 2020|accessdate=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nVad\u00f3cz made his debut for both [[Hungary national under-21 football team|Hungary's under-21]] and [[Hungary national football team|the full side]] in 2004. He scored his first goal for the latter a year later, in a 3\u20130 [[Exhibition game|friendly]] win over [[Antigua and Barbuda national football team|Antigua and Barbuda]] in [[Miami, Florida]].\n\n===International goals===\n(Hungary score listed first, score column indicates score after each Vad\u00f3cz goal)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=25960|title=Vad\u00f3cz Kriszti\u00e1n|publisher=European Football|accessdate=12 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:85%;\"\n! No !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1. || 18 December 2005 || [[Riccardo Silva Stadium|Riccardo Silva]], [[Miami]], [[United States]] || {{fb|ATG}} || align=center | '''1'''\u20130 || align=center | 3\u20130 || [[Exhibition game|Friendly]]\n|-\n| 2. || 24 May 2008 || [[Pusk\u00e1s Ferenc Stadion (1953)|Ferenc Pusk\u00e1s]], [[Budapest]], Hungary || {{fb|GRE}} || align=center | '''3'''\u20131 || align=center | 3\u20132 || Friendly\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n'''Honv\u00e9d'''\n*[[Hungarian Cup]] Runner-up: 2003\u201304\n\n'''Kitchee'''\n*[[Hong Kong Premier League]]: [[2016\u201317 Hong Kong Premier League|2016\u201317]], [[2017\u201318 Hong Kong Premier League|2017\u201318]]\n*[[Hong Kong Senior Challenge Shield]]: [[2016\u201317 Hong Kong Senior Challenge Shield|2016\u201317]], [[2018\u201319 Hong Kong Senior Challenge Shield|2018\u201319]]\n*[[Hong Kong FA Cup]]: [[2016\u201317 Hong Kong FA Cup|2016\u201317]], [[2017\u201318 Hong Kong FA Cup|2017\u201318]], [[2018-19 Hong Kong FA Cup|2018\u201319]]\n*[[Sapling Cup]]: [[2017\u201318 Sapling Cup|2017\u201318]]\n*Hong Kong Community Shield: 2017<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hkfa.com/news_details2/15234|title=2017 HKJC Community Cup \u2013 Kitchee 2:1 Eastern Long Lion|publisher=[[Hong Kong Football Association]]|date=23 September 2017|accessdate=20 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Individual===\n*[[Hong Kong Top Footballer Awards#Footballer of the Year|Hong Kong Footballer of the Year]]: 2018\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{LFP|id=vadocz-krisztian}}\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n*{{BDFutbol|8515}}\n*{{NFT player|id=10571}}\n*{{FIFA player|217241}}\n*{{Soccerway|krisztian-vadocz/1416}}\n\n{{Pe\u00f1arol squad}}\n{{Hong Kong Footballer of the Year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vadocz, Krisztian}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Budapest]]\n[[Category:Hungarian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Nemzeti Bajnoks\u00e1g I players]]\n[[Category:Budapest Honv\u00e9d FC players]]\n[[Category:Championnat National 2 players]]\n[[Category:AJ Auxerre players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Motherwell F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Eredivisie players]]\n[[Category:NEC Nijmegen players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:CA Osasuna players]]\n[[Category:Deportivo Alav\u00e9s players]]\n[[Category:Danish Superliga players]]\n[[Category:Odense Boldklub players]]\n[[Category:Indian Super League players]]\n[[Category:FC Pune City players]]\n[[Category:Mumbai City FC players]]\n[[Category:Swiss Super League players]]\n[[Category:Grasshopper Club Z\u00fcrich players]]\n[[Category:A-League players]]\n[[Category:Perth Glory FC players]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Kitchee SC players]]\n[[Category:Uruguayan Primera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Pe\u00f1arol players]]\n[[Category:Hungary under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Hungary international footballers]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in France]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in India]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in Australia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Uruguay]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate sportspeople in France]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate sportspeople in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate sportspeople in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate sportspeople in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate sportspeople in India]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate sportspeople in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate sportspeople in Australia]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate sportspeople in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate sportspeople in Uruguay]]\n", "name_user": "Quite A Character", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHonours:Minor here.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kriszti%C3%A1n_Vad%C3%B3cz"}
{"title_page": "Western Schism", "text_new": "{{short description|Split within the Catholic Church from 1378 to 1417}}\n{{For|the East\u2013West Schism of 1054|East\u2013West Schism}}\n{{Expand French|date=December 2018}}\n[[File:Western schism 1378-1417.svg|thumb|300px|Map showing support for Avignon (red) and Rome (blue) during the Western Schism; this breakdown is accurate until the [[Council of Pisa]] (1409), which created a third line of claimants.]]\nThe '''Western Schism''', also called '''Papal Schism''', '''Great Occidental Schism''' and '''Schism of 1378''' ({{Lang-la|Magnum schisma occidentale, Ecclesiae occidentalis schisma}}), was a split within the [[Roman Catholic Church|Catholic Church]] lasting from 1378 to 1417<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/640848/Western-Schism |title=Western Schism |publisher=britannica.com |date=December 2014}}</ref> in which two men (by 1410 three) simultaneously claimed to be the true [[pope]], and each [[Excommunication|excommunicated]] one another. Driven by authoritative politics rather than any [[History of Catholic dogmatic theology|theological disagreement]], the [[Schism (religion)|schism]] was ended by the [[Council of Constance]] (1414\u20131418). For a time these rival claims to the papal throne damaged the reputation of the office.<ref> Johannes Fried (2015), \"Chapter 7: The Long Century of Papal Schisms\", in: ''The Middle Ages''. Cambridge, Massachusetts: Harvard University Press. pp. 167\u2013237.</ref>\n\nThe affair is sometimes referred to as the ''Great Schism'', although this term is typically reserved for the more enduring [[East\u2013West Schism]] of 1054 between the Western Churches answering to the [[See of Rome]] and the [[Greek Orthodox Church]]es of the East.\n\n==Origin==\nThe [[Schism (religion)|schism]] in the Western Roman Church resulted from the return of the papacy to [[Rome]] by [[Pope Gregory XI|Gregory XI]] on January 17, 1377.<ref>J.N.D. Kelly, ''Oxford Dictionary of the Popes'', p. 227.</ref> The [[Avignon Papacy]] had developed a reputation for corruption that estranged major parts of Western [[Christendom]]. This reputation can be attributed to perceptions of predominant French influence, and to the papal [[Curia (Roman Catholic Church)|curia]]'s efforts to extend its powers of patronage and increase its revenues.{{citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\nPope Gregory announced his intention to return to Avignon, just after the Easter celebrations of 1378.<ref>Ferdinand Gregorovius  (1906), Annie Hamilton (ed.), ''History of the City of Rome in the Middle Ages'' [https://archive.org/details/historycityrome03hamigoog/page/n8 Vol. VI, Part II] (London: George Bell 1906), p. 490-491.</ref> This was at the entreaty of his relatives, his friends, and nearly everyone in his retinue. After Pope Gregory XI died in the Vatican palace on 27 March 1378,<ref>{{cite book|author1=Conradus Eubel (ed.)|title=Hierarchia catholica|volume= Tomus 1|date=1913|publisher=Libreria Regensbergiana|location=M\u00fcnster|edition=second|language=Latin|page=[https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol01eubeuoft/page/21 21]|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol01eubeuoft}} {{in lang|la}} </ref> the Romans put into operation a plan to ensure the election of a Roman pope. The pope and his Curia were back in Rome after seventy years in Avignon, and the Romans were prepared to do everything in their power to keep them there. They intended to use intimidation and violence (''impressio et metus'') as their weapons.<ref name=\"Creighton1882\">{{cite book|author=Mandell Creighton|title=The great schism. The Council of Constance, 1378\u20131418|url=https://archive.org/details/ahistorypapacyd01unkngoog|year=1882|publisher=Houghton, Mifflin & Company|pages=[https://archive.org/details/ahistorypapacyd01unkngoog/page/n75 49]\u201368}}</ref> On April 8, 1378 the [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|cardinals]] elected a [[Naples|Neapolitan]] when no viable Roman candidate presented himself. [[Pope Urban VI|Urban VI]], born Bartolomeo Prignano, the [[Archbishop of Bari]], was elected. Urban had been a respected administrator in the papal [[Apostolic Chancery|chancery]] at Avignon, but as pope he proved suspicious, reformist, and prone to violent outbursts of temper.<ref>Cardinal Hugues de Montelais stated that he had a mental reservation against Bartolomeo Prignano, on the grounds that he was \"unsuitable\", due to his temperament and temper: \"dixit in vera conscientia sua quod ante ingressum conclavis nec post nunquam habuit in mente consentiendi in eum nec eligendi eum, nec etiam cum esset in conclave nominavit eum, quia agnoscebat eum quod esset melancholicus et furiosus homo.\" Stephanus Baluzius [\u00c9tienne Baluze], ''Vitae Paparum Avinionensium'' Volume 1 (Paris: apud Franciscum Muguet 1693) column 1270.</ref> Many of the cardinals who had elected him soon regretted their decision: the majority removed themselves from Rome to [[Anagni]], where, even though Urban was still reigning, they elected Robert of Geneva as a rival pope on September 20 of the same year, claiming that the election of Urban was invalid because it had been done for fear of the rioting crowds.<ref>T. Wilson-Smith, ''Joan of Arc'', p. 24</ref> Elected pope at [[Fondi]] on 20 September 1378 by the French cardinals,<ref>''Seeking Legitimacy:Art and Manuscripts for the Popes in Avignon from 1378 to 1417'', Cathleen A. Fleck</ref><ref>''A Companion to the Great Western Schism (1378\u20131417)'',  ed. [[Jo\u00eblle Rollo-Koster]], Thomas M. Izbicki, (Brill, 2009), 241.</ref>  unable to maintain himself in Italy, Robert took the name [[Antipope Clement VII|Clement VII]] and reestablished a papal court in Avignon, where he became dependent on the French court.<ref>{{CE1913 |last=Weber |first=Nicholas Aloysius |wstitle=Robert of Geneva |volume=13}}</ref> Clement had the immediate support of Queen [[Joanna I of Naples|Joanna of Naples]] and of several of the Italian barons. [[Charles V of France]], who seems to have been sounded beforehand on the choice of the Roman pontiff, soon became his warmest protector. Clement eventually succeeded in winning to his cause Castile, Aragon, Navarre, a great part of the Latin East, and Flanders. Scotland supported Clement because England supported Urban.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=UX4U8QCJUW4C&pg=PA157&dq=Antipope+Clement+VII&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjvwZaVksLiAhXqmuAKHeQrDVk4ChDoAQhPMAc#v=onepage&q=Antipope%20Clement%20VII&f=false Walsh, Michael J. and Walsh, Michael. ''The Cardinals: Thirteen Centuries of the Men Behind the Papal Throne'', Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing, 2011, p. 157]{{ISBN|9780802829412}}</ref>\n\nThe pair of elections threw the Church into turmoil. There had been rival [[antipope]] claimants to the papacy before, but most of them had been appointed by various rival factions; in this case, a single group of leaders of the Church had created both the pope and the antipope.<ref>Johannes Fried (2015) pp. 167\u2013237. '''The Long Century of Papal Schisms'''. The Middle Ages. Cambridge, Massachusetts: Harvard University Press. {{Page needed|date=September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe conflicts quickly escalated from a church problem to a diplomatic crisis that divided Europe. Secular leaders had to choose which claimant they would recognize:\n*Avignon: [[Kingdom of France|France]], [[Crown of Aragon|Aragon]], [[Crown of Castile|Castile and Le\u00f3n]], [[Kingdom of Cyprus|Cyprus]], [[Duchy of Burgundy|Burgundy]], [[County of Savoy|Savoy]], [[Kingdom of Naples|Naples]], [[Kingdom of Scotland|Scotland]] and [[Owain Glynd\u0175r]]'s rebellion in [[Wales]] recognized the Avignon claimant;\n*Rome: [[Denmark]], [[Kingdom of England|England]], [[County of Flanders|Flanders]], the [[Holy Roman Empire]], [[Kingdom of Hungary in the Middle Ages|Hungary]], [[History of Ireland (1169\u20131536)|Ireland]] (English dominion), [[Kingdom of Norway|Norway]], [[Kingdom of Portugal|Portugal]], [[Kingdom of Poland (1025\u20131385)|Poland]] (later [[Polish-Lithuanian union|Poland-Lithuania]]), [[Kingdom of Sweden|Sweden]], [[Republic of Venice]], and other City States of [[northern Italy]], recognized the Roman claimant.\n\nIn the Iberian Peninsula there were the [[Fernandine Wars]] (''Guerras fernandinas'') and the [[1383\u20131385 Crisis]] in [[Kingdom of Portugal|Portugal]], during which dynastic opponents supported rival claimants to the papal office.\n===Timeline===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|+ Western Schism\n|-\n| <timeline>\nImageSize = width:800 height:130\nPlotArea = width:640 height:110 left:80 bottom:20\nAlignBars = justify \n\nColors = \n  id:avignon value:rgb(0.6,1,1)\n  id:rome value:rgb(0.6,1,0.6)\n  id:pisan value:rgb(1,1,0.6)\n  id:black value:black\n  id:gray value:rgb(0.9,0.9,0.9)\n\nPeriod = from:1368 till:1432\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal\nScaleMajor = unit:year increment:10 start:1370\nScaleMinor = unit:year increment:1 start:1368\n\nBarData =\n  bar:Avignon text:[[Avignon]]:\n  bar:Rome text:[[Rome]]:\n  bar:Pisan text:[[Pisa]]:\n\nPlotData =\n  align:center textcolor:black fontsize:S mark:(line,black) width:35 shift:(0,-5)\n\n  bar:Avignon color:avignon\n  from:1378.7 till:1394.7 text:[[Antipope Clement VII|Clement VII]]\n  from:1394.7 till:1417.6 text:[[Antipope Benedict XIII|Benedict XIII]]\n\n  bar:Rome color:gray\n  from:1371.0 till:1378.3 text:[[Gregory XI]]\n\n  bar:Rome color:rome\n  from:1378.3 till:1389.8 text:[[Urban VI]]\n  from:1389.8 till:1404.8 text:[[Boniface IX]]\n  from:1404.8 till:1406.9 text:\"[[Pope Innocent VII|Innocent VII]]\" shift:(0,1)\n  from:1406.9 till:1415.5 text:\"[[Gregory XII]]\" shift:(2,-5)\n\n  bar:Rome color:gray\n  from:1417.9 till:1431.2 text:[[Pope Martin V|Martin V]]\n\n  bar:Pisan color:pisan\n  from:1409.5 till:1410.3 text:\"[[Antipope Alexander V|Alexander V]]\" shift:(-31,-5)\n  from:1410.3 till:1415.5 text:\"[[Antipope John XXIII|John XXIII]]\" shift:(0,1)\n</timeline>\n|}\n\n==Consequences==\n[[Image:Habemus Papam 1415.jpg|thumb|''[[Habemus Papam]]'' at the Council of Constance]]\nSustained by such national and factional rivalries throughout Catholic Christianity, the schism continued after the deaths of both Urban VI in 1389 and Clement VII in 1394. [[Boniface IX]], who was crowned at Rome in 1389, and [[Antipope Benedict XIII|Benedict XIII]], who reigned in Avignon from 1394, maintained their rival courts. When Pope Boniface died in 1404, the eight cardinals of the Roman conclave offered to refrain from electing a new pope if Benedict would resign; but when Benedict's legates refused on his behalf, the Roman party then proceeded to elect Pope [[Pope Innocent VII|Innocent VII]].\n\nIn the intense partisanship, characteristic of the Middle Ages, the schism engendered a fanatical hatred noted by [[Johan Huizinga]]:<ref>Huizinga, ''[[The Autumn of the Middle Ages|The Waning of the Middle Ages]]'', 1924:14</ref> when the town of [[Bruges]] went over to the \"obedience\" of Avignon, a great number of people left to follow their trade in a city of Urbanist allegiance; in the 1382 [[Battle of Roosebeke]], the [[oriflamme]], which might only be unfurled in a holy cause, was taken up against the [[Flemings]], because they were Urbanists and thus viewed by the French as schismatics.{{Citation needed|reason=the articles about the battle doesn't mention the reason, the article about the oriflamme doesn't mention the condition|date=July 2017}}\n\nEfforts were made to end the Schism through force or diplomacy. The French crown even tried to coerce Benedict XIII, whom it supported, into resigning. None of these remedies worked. The suggestion that a [[Ecumenical Council|church council]] should resolve the Schism, first made in 1378, was not adopted at first, because [[canon law]] required that a pope call a council.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}} Eventually theologians like [[Pierre d'Ailly]] and Jean Gerson, as well as canon lawyers like [[Francesco Zabarella]], adopted arguments that equity permitted the Church to act for its own welfare in defiance of the [[letter of the law]].\n\nEventually the cardinals of both factions secured an agreement that Benedict and Pope [[Gregory XII]] (successor to Innocent VII) would meet at [[Savona]]. They balked at the last moment, and both groups of cardinals abandoned their preferred leaders. [[Council of Pisa|A church council was held]] at [[Pisa]] in 1409 under the auspices of the cardinals to try solving the dispute. At the fifteenth session, 5 June 1409, the Council of Pisa attempted to depose both Pope and antipope as schismatical, heretical, perjured and scandalous,<ref>J. P. Adams, [http://www.csun.edu/~hcfll004/1410_Council_Pisa_XV.html ''Council of Pisa: Deposition of Benedict XIII and Gregory XII''], with additional references. Retrieved 02/26/2106.</ref> but it then added to the problem by electing a second antipope, [[Antipope Alexander V|Alexander V]]. He reigned briefly from June 26, 1409, to his death in 1410, when he was succeeded by antipope [[Antipope John XXIII|John XXIII]], who won some but not universal support.\n\n==Resolution==\n{{unreferenced section|date=June 2015}}\nFinally,  [[Council of Constance|a council was convened]] by Pisan antipope [[Antipope John XXIII|John XXIII]] in 1414 at [[Constance]] to resolve the issue. This was endorsed by Pope [[Gregory XII]], thus ensuring the legitimacy of any election. The council, advised by the theologian [[Jean Gerson]], secured the resignations of John XXIII and Pope Gregory XII, who resigned in 1415, while [[excommunication|excommunicating]] the second antipope, [[Antipope Benedict XIII|Benedict XIII]], who refused to step down. The Council elected [[Pope Martin V]] in 1417, essentially ending the schism. Nonetheless, the Crown of Aragon did not recognize Pope Martin V and continued to recognize Benedict XIII. Archbishops loyal to Benedict XIII subsequently elected [[Antipope Benedict XIV]] (Bernard Garnier) and three followers simultaneously elected [[Antipope Clement VIII]], but the Western Schism was by then practically over. Clement VIII resigned in 1429 and apparently recognized Martin V.\n\nThe line of Roman popes is now recognized as the legitimate line, but confusion on this point continued until the 19th century. Pope [[Pius II]] (died 1464) decreed that no appeal could be made from pope to council, to avoid any future attempts to undo a papal election by anyone but the elected pope. No such crisis has arisen since the 15th century, and so there has been no need to revisit this decision. The alternate papal claimants have become known in history as [[antipope]]s. Those of Avignon were dismissed by Rome early on, but the Pisan popes were included in the ''Annuario Pontificio'' as popes well into the 20th century. Thus the Borgia pope [[Pope Alexander VI|Alexander VI]] took his regnal name in sequence after the Pisan Alexander V.\n\nGregory XII's resignation (in 1415) was the last time a pope resigned until [[Pope Benedict XVI|Benedict XVI]] in 2013.\n\n== Aftermath ==\nAfter its resolution, the Western Schism still affected the Catholic Church for years to come. One of the most significant of these involved the emergence of the theory called [[conciliarism]], founded on the success of the [[Council of Constance]], which effectively ended the conflict. This new reform movement held that a general council is superior to the pope on the strength of its capability to settle things even in the early church such as the case in 681 when [[Pope Honorius I|Pope Honorius]] was condemned by a council called Constantinople III.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Pilgrim Church: A Popular History of Catholic Christianity|last=Bausch|first=William|last2=Cannon|first2=Carol Ann|last3=Obach|first3=Robert|publisher=Twenty-Third Publications|year=1989|isbn=0896223957|location=Mystic, CT|pages=211}}</ref> There are theorists such as [[Jean Gerson|John Gerson]] who explained that the priests and the church itself are the sources of the papal power and, thus, the church should be able to correct, punish, and, if necessary, depose a pope.<ref>Bausch, Cannon, & Oback, p. 211.</ref> For years, the so-called conciliarists have challenged the authority of the pope and they became more relevant after a convened council also known as the [[Council of Florence]] (1439\u20131445) became instrumental in achieving ecclesial union between the Catholic Church and the churches of the East.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Hidden Manna: A Theology of the Eucharist|last=O'Connor|first=James Thomas|publisher=Ignatius Press|year=2005|isbn=1586170767|location=San Francisco|pages=204}}</ref>\n\nThere was also a marked decline in morality and discipline within the church. Scholars note that although the Western Schism did not directly cause such a phenomenon, it was a gradual development rooted in the conflict, effectively eroding the church authority and its capacity to proclaim the gospel.<ref>{{Cite book|title=An Introduction to Canon Law|last=Coriden|first=James|publisher=Paulist Press|year=2004|isbn=0809142562|location=New York|pages=21}}</ref> This was further aggravated by the dissension caused by the [[Reformation|Protestant Reformation]].\n\n==Historiography==\n\nAccording to Broderick, in 1987:\n{{quote|Doubt still shrouds the validity of the three rival lines of pontiffs during the four decades subsequent to the still disputed papal election of 1378. This makes suspect the credentials of the cardinals created by the Roman, Avignon, and Pisan claimants to the Apostolic See. Unity was finally restored without a definitive solution to the question; for the Council of Constance succeeded in terminating the Western Schism, not by declaring which of the three claimants was the rightful one, but by eliminating all of them by forcing their abdication or deposition, and then setting up a novel arrangement for choosing a new pope acceptable to all sides. To this day the Church has never made any official, authoritative pronouncement about the papal lines of succession for this confusing period; nor has Martin V or any of his successors. Modern scholars are not agreed in their solutions, although they tend to favor the Roman line.<ref>Broderick, J.F. 1987. \"The Sacred College of Cardinals: Size and Geographical Composition (1099\u20131986).\" ''Archivum historiae Pontificiae'', '''25''': p. 14.</ref>}}\n\nThe ''[[Annuario Pontificio]]'' has historically regarded the Roman line as legitimate and recognized the decisions of the [[Council of Pisa]] (1409). Until the mid-20th century, the ''Annuario Pontificio'' listed the last three popes of the schism as [[Pope Gregory XII|Gregory XII]] (1406\u20131409), [[Antipope Alexander V|Alexander V]] (1409\u20131410), and [[Antipope John XXIII|John XXIII]] (1410\u20131415).<ref>{{cite book |title=Annuario pontificio per l'anno 1942 |date=1942 |location=Rome |page=21 |quote=205. Gregorio XII, Veneto, Correr (c. 1406, cess\u00f2 a. 1409, m. 1417) - Pont. a. 2, m. 6. g. 4. 206. Alessandro V, dell'Isola di Candia, Filargo (c. 1409, m. 1410). - Pont. m. 10, g. 8. 207. Giovanni XXII o XXIII o XXIV, Napoletano, Cossa (c. 1410, cess\u00f2 dal pontificare 29 mag. 1415}}</ref> However, the schism was reinterpreted when [[Pope John XXIII]] (1958\u20131963) chose to reuse the ordinal XXIII, citing \"twenty-two Johns of indisputable legitimacy.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=I Choose John ... |url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,938062,00.html |work=Time |date=10 November 1958 | page=91}}</ref> This is reflected in modern editions of the ''Annuario Pontificio'', which extend Gregory XII's reign to 1415. Alexander V and the first John XXIII are now considered to be antipopes.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Gail, Marzieh (1969). ''The Three Popes: An Account of the Great Schism''. New York, 1969.\n*Gayet, Louis (1889). ''Le grand schisme d'Occident.'' 2 volumes. Paris-Florence-Berlin: Loescher et Seeber 1889. {{in lang|fr}}\n*Prerovsky, Ulderico (1960). ''L' elezione di Urbano VI, e l' insorgere dello scisma d' occidente''. Roma: Societ\u00e0 alla Biblioteca Vallicelliana 1960. {{in lang|it}}\n*[[Jo\u00eblle Rollo-Koster|Rollo-Koster, Jo\u00eblle ]] and Izbicki, Thomas M. (editors) (2009). ''A Companion to the Great Western Schism (1378\u20131417)'' Leiden: Brill, 2009.\n*Smith, John Holland (1970). ''The Great Schism: 1378''. New York 1970.\n*Ullman, Walter (1948). ''The Origins of the Great Schism: A study in fourteenth century ecclesiastical history''. Hamden, Conn: Archon Books, 1967 (reprint of 1948 original publication)) [strongly partisan for Urban VI].\n*Valois, No\u00ebl (1890). \"L' \u00e9lection d'Urbain VI. et les origines du Grand Schisme d'Occident,\" in: ''Revue des questions historiques'' 48 (1890), pp. 353\u2013420. {{in lang|fr}}\n*Valois, No\u00ebl (1896). ''La France et le Grand Schisme d'Occident''. Tome premier. Paris: Alphonse Picard 1896.\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Catholicism}}\n*[https://archive.org/details/ageofgreatwester08lock The Age of the Great Western Schism]\n*[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/13539a.htm Catholic Encyclopedia article]\n\n{{Periods of papal history}}\n{{History of the Catholic Church}}\n{{Catholicism}}\n{{Christian History|collapsed}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list=\n{{WesternSchism}}\n{{Antipopes}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Western Schism| Western Schism]]\n[[Category:1370s in Europe]]\n[[Category:1378 in Europe]]\n[[Category:1380s in Europe]]\n[[Category:1390s in Europe]]\n[[Category:1400s in Europe]]\n[[Category:1410s in Europe]]\n[[Category:1417 in Europe]]\n[[Category:14th-century Catholicism]]\n[[Category:15th-century Catholicism]]\n[[Category:Avignon Papacy]]\n[[Category:Christian terminology]]\n[[Category:History of the papacy]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Split within the Catholic Church from 1378 to 1417}}\n{{For|the East\u2013West Schism of 1054|East\u2013West Schism}}\n{{Expand French|date=December 2018}}\n[[File:Western schism 1378-1417.svg|thumb|300px|Map showing support for Avignon (red) and Rome (blue) during the Western Schism; this breakdown is accurate until the [[Council of Pisa]] (1409), which created a third line of claimants.]]\nThe '''Western Schism''', also called '''Papal Schism''', '''Great Occidental Schism''' and '''Schism of 1378''' ({{Lang-la|Magnum schisma occidentale, Ecclesiae occidentalis schisma}}), was a split within the [[Roman Catholic Church|Catholic Church]] lasting from 1378 to 1417<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/640848/Western-Schism |title=Western Schism |publisher=britannica.com |date=December 2014}}</ref> in which two men (by 1410 three) simultaneously claimed to be the true [[pope]], and each [[Excommunication|excommunicated]] one another. Driven by authoritative politics rather than any [[History of Catholic dogmatic theology|theological disagreement]], the [[Schism (religion)|schism]] was ended by the [[Council of Constance]] (1414\u20131418). For a time these rival claims to the papal throne damaged the reputation of the office.<ref> Johannes Fried (2015), \"Chapter 7: The Long Century of Papal Schisms\", in: ''The Middle Ages''. Cambridge, Massachusetts: Harvard University Press. pp. 167\u2013237.</ref>\n\nThe affair is sometimes referred to as the ''Great Schism'', although this term is typically reserved for the more enduring [[East\u2013West Schism]] of 1054 between the Western Churches answering to the [[See of Rome]] and the [[Greek Orthodox Church]]es of the East.\n\n==Origin==\nThe [[Schism (religion)|schism]] in the Western Roman Church resulted from the return of the papacy to [[Rome]] by [[Pope Gregory XI|Gregory XI]] on January 17, 1377.<ref>J.N.D. Kelly, ''Oxford Dictionary of the Popes'', p. 227.</ref> The [[Avignon Papacy]] had developed a reputation for corruption that estranged major parts of Western [[Christendom]]. This reputation can be attributed to perceptions of predominant French influence, and to the papal [[Curia (Roman Catholic Church)|curia]]'s efforts to extend its powers of patronage and increase its revenues.{{citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\nPope Gregory announced his intention to return to Avignon, just after the Easter celebrations of 1378.<ref>Ferdinand Gregorovius  (1906), Annie Hamilton (ed.), ''History of the City of Rome in the Middle Ages'' [https://archive.org/details/historycityrome03hamigoog/page/n8 Vol. VI, Part II] (London: George Bell 1906), p. 490-491.</ref> This was at the entreaty of his relatives, his friends, and nearly everyone in his retinue. After Pope Gregory XI died in the Vatican palace on 27 March 1378,<ref>{{cite book|author1=Conradus Eubel (ed.)|title=Hierarchia catholica|volume= Tomus 1|date=1913|publisher=Libreria Regensbergiana|location=M\u00fcnster|edition=second|language=Latin|page=[https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol01eubeuoft/page/21 21]|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol01eubeuoft}} {{in lang|la}} </ref> the Romans put into operation a plan to ensure the election of a Roman pope. The pope and his Curia were back in Rome after seventy years in Avignon, and the Romans were prepared to do everything in their power to keep them there. They intended to use intimidation and violence (''impressio et metus'') as their weapons.<ref name=\"Creighton1882\">{{cite book|author=Mandell Creighton|title=The great schism. The Council of Constance, 1378\u20131418|url=https://archive.org/details/ahistorypapacyd01unkngoog|year=1882|publisher=Houghton, Mifflin & Company|pages=[https://archive.org/details/ahistorypapacyd01unkngoog/page/n75 49]\u201368}}</ref> On April 8, 1378 the [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|cardinals]] elected a [[Naples|Neapolitan]] when no viable Roman candidate presented himself. [[Pope Urban VI|Urban VI]], born Bartolomeo Prignano, the [[Archbishop of Bari]], was elected. Urban had been a respected administrator in the papal [[Apostolic Chancery|chancery]] at Avignon, but as pope he proved suspicious, reformist, and prone to violent outbursts of temper.<ref>Cardinal Hugues de Montelais stated that he had a mental reservation against Bartolomeo Prignano, on the grounds that he was \"unsuitable\", due to his temperament and temper: \"dixit in vera conscientia sua quod ante ingressum conclavis nec post nunquam habuit in mente consentiendi in eum nec eligendi eum, nec etiam cum esset in conclave nominavit eum, quia agnoscebat eum quod esset melancholicus et furiosus homo.\" Stephanus Baluzius [\u00c9tienne Baluze], ''Vitae Paparum Avinionensium'' Volume 1 (Paris: apud Franciscum Muguet 1693) column 1270.</ref> Many of the cardinals who had elected him soon regretted their decision: the majority removed themselves from Rome to [[Anagni]], where, even though Urban was still reigning, they elected Robert of Geneva as a rival pope on September 20 of the same year, claiming that the election of Urban was invalid because it had been done for fear of the rioting crowds.<ref>T. Wilson-Smith, ''Joan of Arc'', p. 24</ref> Elected pope at [[Fondi]] on 20 September 1378 by the French cardinals,<ref>''Seeking Legitimacy:Art and Manuscripts for the Popes in Avignon from 1378 to 1417'', Cathleen A. Fleck</ref><ref>''A Companion to the Great Western Schism (1378\u20131417)'',  ed. [[Jo\u00eblle Rollo-Koster]], Thomas M. Izbicki, (Brill, 2009), 241.</ref>  unable to maintain himself in Italy, Robert took the name [[Antipope Clement VII|Clement VII]] and reestablished a papal court in Avignon, where he became dependent on the French court.<ref>{{CE1913 |last=Weber |first=Nicholas Aloysius |wstitle=Robert of Geneva |volume=13}}</ref> Clement had the immediate support of Queen [[Joanna I of Naples|Joanna of Naples]] and of several of the Italian barons. [[Charles V of France]], who seems to have been sounded beforehand on the choice of the Roman pontiff, soon became his warmest protector. Clement eventually succeeded in winning to his cause Castile, Aragon, Navarre, a great part of the Latin East, and Flanders. Scotland supported Clement because England supported Urban.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=UX4U8QCJUW4C&pg=PA157&dq=Antipope+Clement+VII&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjvwZaVksLiAhXqmuAKHeQrDVk4ChDoAQhPMAc#v=onepage&q=Antipope%20Clement%20VII&f=false Walsh, Michael J. and Walsh, Michael. ''The Cardinals: Thirteen Centuries of the Men Behind the Papal Throne'', Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing, 2011, p. 157]{{ISBN|9780802829412}}</ref>\n\nThe pair of elections threw the Church into turmoil. There had been rival [[antipope]] claimants to the papacy before, but most of them had been appointed by various rival factions; in this case, a single group of leaders of the Church had created both the pope and the antipope.<ref>Johannes Fried (2015) pp. 167\u2013237. '''The Long Century of Papal Schisms'''. The Middle Ages. Cambridge, Massachusetts: Harvard University Press. {{Page needed|date=September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe conflicts quickly escalated from a church problem to a diplomatic crisis that divided Europe. Secular leaders had to choose which claimant they would recognize:\n*Avignon: [[Kingdom of France|France]], [[Crown of Aragon|Aragon]], [[Crown of Castile|Castile and Le\u00f3n]], [[Kingdom of Cyprus|Cyprus]], [[Duchy of Burgundy|Burgundy]], [[County of Savoy|Savoy]], [[Kingdom of Naples|Naples]], [[Kingdom of Scotland|Scotland]] and [[Owain Glynd\u0175r]]'s rebellion in [[Wales]] recognized the Avignon claimant;\n*Rome: [[Denmark]], [[Kingdom of England|England]], [[County of Flanders|Flanders]], the [[Holy Roman Empire]], [[Kingdom of Hungary in the Middle Ages|Hungary]], [[History of Ireland (1169\u20131536)|Ireland]] (English dominion), [[Kingdom of Norway|Norway]], [[Kingdom of Portugal|Portugal]], [[Kingdom of Poland (1025\u20131385)|Poland]] (later [[Polish-Lithuanian union|Poland-Lithuania]]), [[Kingdom of Sweden|Sweden]], [[Republic of Venice]], and other City States of [[northern Italy]], recognized the Roman claimant.\n\nIn the Iberian Peninsula there were the [[Fernandine Wars]] (''Guerras fernandinas'') and the [[1383\u20131385 Crisis]] in [[Kingdom of Portugal|Portugal]], during which dynastic opponents supported rival claimants to the papal office.\n===Timeline===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|+ Western Schism\n|-\n| <timeline>\nImageSize = width:800 height:130\nPlotArea = width:640 height:110 left:80 bottom:20\nAlignBars = justify \n\nColors = \n  id:avignon value:rgb(0.6,1,1)\n  id:rome value:rgb(0.6,1,0.6)\n  id:pisan value:rgb(1,1,0.6)\n  id:black value:black\n  id:gray value:rgb(0.9,0.9,0.9)\n\nPeriod = from:1368 till:1432\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal\nScaleMajor = unit:year increment:10 start:1370\nScaleMinor = unit:year increment:1 start:1368\n\nBarData =\n  bar:Avignon text:[[Avignon]]:\n  bar:Rome text:[[Rome]]:\n  bar:Pisan text:[[Pisa]]:\n\nPlotData =\n  align:center textcolor:black fontsize:S mark:(line,black) width:35 shift:(0,-5)\n\n  bar:Avignon color:avignon\n  from:1378.7 till:1394.7 text:[[Antipope Clement VII|Clement VII]]\n  from:1394.7 till:1417.6 text:[[Antipope Benedict XIII|Benedict XIII]]\n\n  bar:Rome color:gray\n  from:1371.0 till:1378.3 text:[[Gregory XI]]\n\n  bar:Rome color:rome\n  from:1378.3 till:1389.8 text:[[Urban VI]]\n  from:1389.8 till:1404.8 text:[[Boniface IX]]\n  from:1404.8 till:1406.9 text:\"[[Pope Innocent VII|Innocent VII]]\" shift:(0,1)\n  from:1406.9 till:1415.5 text:\"[[Gregory XII]]\" shift:(2,-5)\n\n  bar:Rome color:gray\n  from:1417.9 till:1431.2 text:[[Pope Martin V|Martin V]]\n\n  bar:Pisan color:pisan\n  from:1409.5 till:1410.3 text:\"[[Antipope Alexander V|Alexander V]]\" shift:(-31,-5)\n  from:1410.3 till:1415.5 text:\"[[Antipope John XXIII|John XXIII]]\" shift:(0,1)\n</timeline>\n|}\n\n==Consequences==\n[[Image:Habemus Papam 1415.jpg|thumb|''[[Habemus Papam]]'' at the Council of Constance]]\nSustained by such national and factional rivalries throughout Catholic Christianity, the schism continued after the deaths of both Urban VI in 1389 and Clement VII in 1394. [[Boniface IX]], who was crowned at Rome in 1389, and [[Antipope Benedict XIII|Benedict XIII]], who reigned in Avignon from 1394, maintained their rival courts. When Pope Boniface died in 1404, the eight cardinals of the Roman conclave offered to refrain from electing a new pope if Benedict would resign; but when Benedict's legates refused on his behalf, the Roman party then proceeded to elect Pope [[Pope Innocent VII|Innocent VII]].\n\nIn the intense partisanship, characteristic of the Middle Ages, the schism engendered a fanatical hatred noted by [[Johan Huizinga]]:<ref>Huizinga, ''[[The Autumn of the Middle Ages|The Waning of the Middle Ages]]'', 1924:14</ref> when the town of [[Bruges]] went over to the \"obedience\" of Avignon, a great number of people left to follow their trade in a city of Urbanist allegiance; in the 1382 [[Battle of Roosebeke]], the [[oriflamme]], which might only be unfurled in a holy cause, was taken up against the [[Flemings]], because they were Urbanists and thus viewed by the French as schismatics.{{Citation needed|reason=the articles about the battle doesn't mention the reason, the article about the oriflamme doesn't mention the condition|date=July 2017}}\n\nEfforts were made to end the Schism through force or diplomacy. The French crown even tried to coerce Benedict XIII, whom it supported, into resigning. None of these remedies worked. The suggestion that a [[Ecumenical Council|church council]] should resolve the Schism, first made in 1378, was not adopted at first, because [[canon law]] required that a pope call a council.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}} Eventually theologians like [[Pierre d'Ailly]] and Jean Gerson, as well as canon lawyers like [[Francesco Zabarella]], adopted arguments that equity permitted the Church to act for its own welfare in defiance of the [[letter of the law]].\n\nEventually the cardinals of both factions secured an agreement that Benedict and Pope [[Gregory XII]] (successor to Innocent VII) would meet at [[Savona]]. They balked at the last moment, and both groups of cardinals abandoned their preferred leaders. [[Council of Pisa|A church council was held]] at [[Pisa]] in 1409 under the auspices of the cardinals to try solving the dispute. At the fifteenth session, 5 June 1409, the Council of Pisa attempted to depose both Pope and antipope as schismatical, heretical, perjured and scandalous,<ref>J. P. Adams, [http://www.csun.edu/~hcfll004/1410_Council_Pisa_XV.html ''Council of Pisa: Deposition of Benedict XIII and Gregory XII''], with additional references. Retrieved 02/26/2106.</ref> but it then added to the problem by electing a second antipope, [[Antipope Alexander V|Alexander V]]. He reigned briefly from June 26, 1409, to his death in 1410, when he was succeeded by antipope [[Antipope John XXIII|John XXIII]], who won some but not universal support.\n\n==Resolution==\n{{unreferenced section|date=June 2015}}\nFinally,  [[Council of Constance|a council was convened]] by Pisan antipope [[Antipope John XXIII|John XXIII]] in 1414 at [[Constance]] to resolve the issue. This was endorsed by Pope [[Gregory XII]], thus ensuring the legitimacy of any election. The council, advised by the theologian [[Jean Gerson]], secured the resignations of John XXIII and Pope Gregory XII, who resigned in 1415, while [[excommunication|excommunicating]] the second antipope, [[Antipope Benedict XIII|Benedict XIII]], who refused to step down. The Council elected [[Pope Martin V]] in 1417, essentially ending the schism. Nonetheless, the Crown of Aragon did not recognize Pope Martin V and continued to recognize Benedict XIII. Archbishops loyal to Benedict XIII subsequently elected [[Antipope Benedict XIV]] (Bernard Garnier) and three followers simultaneously elected [[Antipope Clement VIII]], but the Western Schism was by then practically over. Clement VIII resigned in 1429 and apparently recognized Martin V.\n\nThe line of Roman popes is now recognized as the legitimate line, but confusion on this point continued until the 19th century. Pope [[Pius II]] (died 1464) decreed that no appeal could be made from pope to council, to avoid any future attempts to undo a papal election by anyone but the elected pope. No such crisis has arisen since the 15th century, and so there has been no need to revisit this decision. The alternate papal claimants have become known in history as [[antipope]]s. Those of Avignon were dismissed by Rome early on, but the Pisan popes were included in the ''Annuario Pontificio'' as popes well into the 20th century. Thus the Borgia pope [[Pope Alexander VI|Alexander VI]] took his regnal name in sequence after the Pisan Alexander V.\n\nGregory XII's resignation (in 1415) was the last time a pope resigned until [[Pope Benedict XVI|Benedict XVI]] in 2013.\n\n== Aftermath ==\nAfter its resolution, the Western Schism still affected the Catholic Church for years to come. One of the most significant of these involved the emergence of the theory called [[conciliarism]], founded on the success of the [[Council of Constance]], which effectively ended the conflict. This new reform movement held that a general council is superior to the pope on the strength of its capability to settle things even in the early church such as the case in 681 when [[Pope Honorius I|Pope Honorius]] was condemned by a council called Constantinople III.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Pilgrim Church: A Popular History of Catholic Christianity|last=Bausch|first=William|last2=Cannon|first2=Carol Ann|last3=Obach|first3=Robert|publisher=Twenty-Third Publications|year=1989|isbn=0896223957|location=Mystic, CT|pages=211}}</ref> There are theorists such as [[Jean Gerson|John Gerson]] who explained that the priests and the church itself are the sources of the papal power and, thus, the church should be able to correct, punish, and, if necessary, depose a pope.<ref>Bausch, Cannon, & Oback, p. 211.</ref> For years, the so-called conciliarists have challenged the authority of the pope and they became more relevant after a convened council also known as the [[Council of Florence]] (1439\u20131445) became instrumental in achieving ecclesial union between the Catholic Church and the churches of the East.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Hidden Manna: A Theology of the Eucharist|last=O'Connor|first=James Thomas|publisher=Ignatius Press|year=2005|isbn=1586170767|location=San Francisco|pages=204}}</ref>\n\nThere was also a marked decline in morality and discipline within the church. Scholars note that although the Western Schism did not directly cause such a phenomenon, it was a gradual development rooted in the conflict, effectively eroding the church authority and its capacity to proclaim the gospel.<ref>{{Cite book|title=An Introduction to Canon Law|last=Coriden|first=James|publisher=Paulist Press|year=2004|isbn=0809142562|location=New York|pages=21}}</ref> This was further aggravated by the dissension caused by the [[Reformation|Protestant Reformation]].\n\n==Historiography==\n\nAccording to Broderick, in 1987:\n{{quote|Doubt still shrouds the validity of the three rival lines of pontiffs during the four decades subsequent to the still disputed papal election of 1378. This makes suspect the credentials of the cardinals created by the Roman, Avignon, and Pisan claimants to the Apostolic See. Unity was finally restored without a definitive solution to the question; for the Council of Constance succeeded in terminating the Western Schism, not by declaring which of the three claimants was the rightful one, but by eliminating all of them by forcing their abdication or deposition, and then setting up a novel arrangement for choosing a new pope acceptable to all sides. To this day the Church has never made any official, authoritative pronouncement about the papal lines of succession for this confusing period; nor has Martin V or any of his successors. Modern scholars are not agreed in their solutions, although they tend to favor the Roman line.<ref>Broderick, J.F. 1987. \"The Sacred College of Cardinals: Size and Geographical Composition (1099\u20131986).\" ''Archivum historiae Pontificiae'', '''25''': p. 14.</ref>}}\n\nThe ''[[Annuario Pontificio]]'' has historically regarded the Roman line as legitimate and recognized the decisions of the [[Council of Pisa]] (1409). Until the mid-20th century, the ''Annuario Pontificio'' listed the last three popes of the schism as [[Pope Gregory XII|Gregory XII]] (1406\u20131409), [[Antipope Alexander V|Alexander V]] (1409\u20131410), and [[Antipope John XXIII|John XXIII]] (1410\u20131415).<ref>{{cite book |title=Annuario pontificio per l'anno 1942 |date=1942 |location=Rome |page=21 |quote=205. Gregorio XII, Veneto, Correr (c. 1406, cesso a. 1409, m. 1417) - Pont. a. 2, m. 6. g. 4. 206. Alessandro V, dell'Isola di Candia, Filargo (c. 1409, m. 1410). - Pont. m. 10, g. 8. 207. Giovanni XXII o XXIII o XXIV, Napoletano, Cossa (c. 1410, cesso dal pontificare 29 mag. 1415}}</ref> However, the schism was reinterpreted when [[Pope John XXIII]] (1958\u20131963) chose to reuse the ordinal XXIII, citing \"twenty-two Johns of indisputable legitimacy.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=I Choose John ... |url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,938062,00.html |work=Time |date=10 November 1958 | page=91}}</ref> This is reflected in modern editions of the ''Annuario Pontificio'', which extend Gregory XII's reign to 1415. Alexander V and the first John XXIII are now considered to be antipopes.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Gail, Marzieh (1969). ''The Three Popes: An Account of the Great Schism''. New York, 1969.\n*Gayet, Louis (1889). ''Le grand schisme d'Occident.'' 2 volumes. Paris-Florence-Berlin: Loescher et Seeber 1889. {{in lang|fr}}\n*Prerovsky, Ulderico (1960). ''L' elezione di Urbano VI, e l' insorgere dello scisma d' occidente''. Roma: Societ\u00e0 alla Biblioteca Vallicelliana 1960. {{in lang|it}}\n*[[Jo\u00eblle Rollo-Koster|Rollo-Koster, Jo\u00eblle ]] and Izbicki, Thomas M. (editors) (2009). ''A Companion to the Great Western Schism (1378\u20131417)'' Leiden: Brill, 2009.\n*Smith, John Holland (1970). ''The Great Schism: 1378''. New York 1970.\n*Ullman, Walter (1948). ''The Origins of the Great Schism: A study in fourteenth century ecclesiastical history''. Hamden, Conn: Archon Books, 1967 (reprint of 1948 original publication)) [strongly partisan for Urban VI].\n*Valois, No\u00ebl (1890). \"L' \u00e9lection d'Urbain VI. et les origines du Grand Schisme d'Occident,\" in: ''Revue des questions historiques'' 48 (1890), pp. 353\u2013420. {{in lang|fr}}\n*Valois, No\u00ebl (1896). ''La France et le Grand Schisme d'Occident''. Tome premier. Paris: Alphonse Picard 1896.\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Catholicism}}\n*[https://archive.org/details/ageofgreatwester08lock The Age of the Great Western Schism]\n*[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/13539a.htm Catholic Encyclopedia article]\n\n{{Periods of papal history}}\n{{History of the Catholic Church}}\n{{Catholicism}}\n{{Christian History|collapsed}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list=\n{{WesternSchism}}\n{{Antipopes}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Western Schism| Western Schism]]\n[[Category:1370s in Europe]]\n[[Category:1378 in Europe]]\n[[Category:1380s in Europe]]\n[[Category:1390s in Europe]]\n[[Category:1400s in Europe]]\n[[Category:1410s in Europe]]\n[[Category:1417 in Europe]]\n[[Category:14th-century Catholicism]]\n[[Category:15th-century Catholicism]]\n[[Category:Avignon Papacy]]\n[[Category:Christian terminology]]\n[[Category:History of the papacy]]\n", "name_user": "Tozar80", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistoriography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_Schism"}
{"title_page": "Anthony Perkins", "text_new": "{{Other people}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Anthony Perkins\n| image         = Anthony Perkins.jpg\n| caption       = Anthony Perkins in 1975, by [[Allan Warren]]\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1932|4|4}}\n| birth_place   = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1992|9|12|1932|4|4}}\n| death_place   = [[Los Angeles]], California, U.S.\n| nationality   = American\n| alma_mater    = [[Columbia University]]\n| years_active  = 1953\u20131992\n| occupation    = {{flatlist|\n*Actor\n*director\n*singer\n}}\n| spouse        = {{marriage|[[Berry Berenson]]|1973}}\n| children      = [[Oz Perkins]]<br>[[Elvis Perkins]]\n| parents       = [[Osgood Perkins]]<br>Janet Esselstyn Rane\n}}\n'''Anthony Perkins''' (April 4, 1932&nbsp;\u2013 September 12, 1992) was an American actor, director and singer. He was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]] for his second film, ''[[Friendly Persuasion (1956 film)|Friendly Persuasion]]'' (1956), but is best remembered for playing [[Norman Bates]] in [[Alfred Hitchcock]]'s ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' (1960) and its [[Psycho (franchise)|three sequels]]. His other films include ''[[Fear Strikes Out]]'' (1957), ''[[The Matchmaker (1958 film)|The Matchmaker]]'' (1958), ''[[On the Beach (1959 film)|On the Beach]]'' (1959), ''[[Tall Story]]'' (1960), ''[[The Trial (1962 film)|The Trial]]'' (1962), ''[[Phaedra (film)|Phaedra]]'' (1962), ''[[Five Miles to Midnight]]'' (1962), ''[[Pretty Poison (film)|Pretty Poison]]'' (1968), ''[[Murder on the Orient Express (1974 film)|Murder on the Orient Express]]'' (1974), ''[[Mahogany (film)|Mahogany]]'' (1975), ''[[The Black Hole]]'' (1979), ''[[North Sea Hijack]]'' (1980) and ''[[Crimes of Passion (1984 film)|Crimes of Passion]]'' (1984).\n\n==Early life==\nPerkins was born in [[New York City]], son of stage and film actor [[Osgood Perkins]] and his wife, Janet Esselstyn (n\u00e9e Rane). His paternal great-grandfather was wood engraver [[Andrew Varick Stout Anthony]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bosarchitecture.com/backbay/beacon/196.html|title=Architecture of 196 Beacon Street, Back Bay, Boston|publisher=BOSarchitecture|accessdate=November 3, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140508025640/http://www.bosarchitecture.com/backbay/beacon/196.html|archivedate=May 8, 2014}}</ref> He was five when his father died.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1937/09/22/archives/osgood-perkins-stage-star-dies-stricken-after-premiere-of-susan-and.html|title=OSGOOD PERKINS, STAGE STAR, DIES; Stricken After Premiere of 'Susan and God,' in Which He Was Leading Man|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 22, 1937|accessdate=April 1, 2008}}{{subscription required|s}}</ref>\n\nPerkins was a descendant of a ''[[Mayflower]]'' passenger, [[John Howland (Mayflower passenger)|John Howland]]. He attended [[Brooks School]], [[Buckingham Browne & Nichols|Browne & Nichols School]], [[Columbia University]] and [[Rollins College]], having moved to [[Boston]] in 1942.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800037259/bio|title=Anthony Perkins Biography |publisher=Yahoo! Movies|accessdate=June 18, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070214112345/http://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800037259/bio|archivedate=February 14, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n{{Refimprove section|date=January 2014}}\nPerkins made his film debut in ''[[The Actress]]'' (1953). The film was a commercial disappointment. Perkins was first really noticed when he replaced [[John Kerr (actor)|John Kerr]] on Broadway in the lead of ''[[Tea and Sympathy (play)|Tea and Sympathy]]'' in 1954. This renewed Hollywood interest in him.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/09/14/obituaries/anthony-perkins-star-of-psycho-and-all-its-sequels-is-dead-at-60.html|title=Anthony Perkins, Star of 'Psycho' And All Its Sequels, Is Dead at 60|last=Myers|first=Steven Lee|date=1992-09-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-10-26|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n===Stardom===\nPerkins gained notice for his second film, ''[[Friendly Persuasion (1956 film)|Friendly Persuasion]]'' (1956), directed by [[William Wyler]], in which he played the son of the lead role, played by [[Gary Cooper]]. The film was a hit and Perkins received the [[Golden Globe Award for New Star of the Year \u2013 Actor]] and an Academy Award nomination.\n\nSubsequently, Perkins starred as troubled former [[Boston Red Sox]] baseball player [[Jimmy Piersall]] in the 1957 biopic ''[[Fear Strikes Out]]'' (1957) and in the two Westerns ''[[The Lonely Man]]'' (1957) (with [[Jack Palance]]) and ''[[The Tin Star]]'' (1957) (with [[Henry Fonda]]).\n\nHe released three [[pop music]] albums and several singles in 1957 and 1958 on [[Epic Records|Epic]] and [[RCA Victor]] under the name Tony Perkins.<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/tony-perkins-mn0000015860|title=Tony Perkins|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=January 9, 2008}}</ref> His single \"Moon-Light Swim\" was a moderate hit in the United States, peaking at number 24 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in 1957.<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/> He showcased his musical talents in ''[[The Matchmaker (1958 film)|The Matchmaker]]'' (1958) with [[Shirley Booth]] and [[Shirley MacLaine]].\n\nA life member of the [[Actors Studio]],<ref>{{cite book|quote=|first=David |last=Garfield|title=A Player's Place: The Story of The Actors Studio|url=https://archive.org/details/playersplacestor00garf|url-access=registration|year=1980|publisher=Macmillan Publishing Co., Inc.|location=New York|isbn=0-02-542650-8|page=[https://archive.org/details/playersplacestor00garf/page/279 279]|chapter=Appendix: Life Members of The Actors Studio as of January 1980}}</ref> Perkins also acted in theater. In 1958, he was nominated for a [[Tony Award]] for [[Tony Award for Best Performance by a Leading Actor in a Play|Best Actor in a Play]] for his performance in ''[[Look Homeward, Angel (play)|Look Homeward, Angel]]'' (1957\u201359) on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]. He played the role of Eugene Gant.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/look-homeward-angel-2660|title=Look Homeward, Angel \u2013 Broadway Play \u2013 Original {{!}} IBDB|website=www.ibdb.com|access-date=2019-02-07}}</ref>\n\nIn film, he appeared in ''[[This Angry Age]]'' (1958) for Columbia and ''[[Desire Under the Elms (film)|Desire Under the Elms]]'' (1958) for Paramount, with [[Sophia Loren]]. He was more happily cast in ''[[The Matchmaker (1958 film)|The Matchmaker]]'' (1958).\n\nPerkins was [[Audrey Hepburn]]'s love interest in ''[[Green Mansions (film)|Green Mansions]]'' (1959), one of Hepburn's few flops. He was a doomed lover in ''[[On the Beach (1959 film)|On the Beach]]'' (1959) and played a college basketball champion in ''[[Tall Story]]'' (1960), best remembered for being [[Jane Fonda]]'s film debut.\n\nOn Broadway, he starred in the [[Frank Loesser]] musical ''[[Greenwillow]]'' (1960), for which he was nominated for another [[Tony Award]] for [[Tony Award for Best Performance by a Leading Actor in a Musical|Best Actor in a Musical]].\n\n===''Psycho''===\nPerkins in youth had a boyish, earnest quality, reminiscent of the young James Stewart, which [[Alfred Hitchcock]] exploited and subverted when the actor starred as [[Norman Bates]] in the film ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' (1960).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=91947125|title=Norman Bates: A Most Terrifying Mama's Boy|work=NPR.org|access-date=2017-10-26|language=en}}</ref> The film was a critical and commercial success, and gained Perkins international fame for his performance as the homicidal owner of the Bates Motel. Perkins' performance gained him the Best Actor Award from the International Board of Motion Picture Reviewers. The role and its multiple sequels affected the remainder of his career.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/09/16/arts/anthony-perkins-s-wife-tells-of-2-years-of-secrecy.html|title=Anthony Perkins's Wife Tells of 2 Years of Secrecy|last=Weinraub|first=Bernard|date=1992-09-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-10-26|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n===Europe===\nPerkins appeared in the film ''[[Goodbye Again (1961 film)|Goodbye Again]]'' (1961) with [[Ingrid Bergman]], which was shot in Paris. His performance won him the Best Actor Award at the 1961 [[Cannes Film Festival]]. The film was a notable success in France but not the US.\n[[File:Evening Primrose Anthony Perkins Charmian Carr 1966 redone.jpg|right|200px|thumb|With [[Charmian Carr]] in ''[[Evening Primrose (musical)|Evening Primrose]]'', 1966]]\n\nHe appeared in a short-lived Broadway play ''Harold'' (1962) then Perkins featured in a sequence of films shot in Europe: ''[[Phaedra (film)|Phaedra]]'' (1962), shot in Greece with [[Melina Mercouri]] and directed by [[Jules Dassin]]; ''[[Five Miles to Midnight]]'' (1962) with [[Sophia Loren]]; [[Orson Welles]]' version of ''[[The Trial (1962 film)|The Trial]]'' (1962, from [[The Trial|the Kafka novel]]); ''[[Le glaive et la balance]]'' (1963), shot in France; ''[[Une ravissante idiote]]'' (1964) with [[Brigitte Bardot]].\n\nHe made a film in Mexico, ''[[The Fool Killer]]'' (1965), then returned to France to make a cameo in ''[[Is Paris Burning? (film)|Is Paris Burning?]]'' (1966).\n\n===Return to the U.S.===\nFor American television, he appeared in ''[[Evening Primrose (musical)|Evening Primrose]]'' (1966). He then went to Broadway to appear in a play by [[Neil Simon]], ''[[The Star-Spangled Girl]]'' (1966\u201367).\n\nPerkins starred in another French film, ''[[The Champagne Murders]]'' (1967) for [[Claude Chabrol]], then made his first Hollywood movie since ''Psycho'', ''[[Pretty Poison (film)|Pretty Poison]]'' (1968) with [[Tuesday Weld]]. The film was not a box office success but has become a notable cult favorite.<ref name=\"perkins\">A PERSONAL REVOLUTION: Anthony Perkins Trying to Mature Boyish Image ANTHONY PERKINS\nThomas, Kevin. Los Angeles Times (1923-Current File) [Los Angeles, Calif] 20 Dec 1967: c1.</ref>\n\n===Supporting actor===\nPerkins moved into supporting roles in Hollywood-feature films, playing [[Chaplain Tappman]] in ''[[Catch-22 (film)|Catch-22]]'' (1970) and appearing in ''[[WUSA (film)|WUSA]]'' (1970). [[Off-Broadway]], he appeared in and directed ''[[Steambath (play)|Steambath]]'' (1970).\n\nHe had the lead in a TV movie, ''[[How Awful About Allan]]'' (1970) and supported [[Charles Bronson]] in the French movie, ''[[Someone Behind the Door]]'' (1971). He starred in Chabrol's ''[[Ten Days' Wonder (film)|Ten Days' Wonder]]'' (1971).\n\nPerkins was reunited with Weld when he supported her in ''[[Play It as It Lays (film)|Play It as It Lays]]'' (1972). He was also in ''[[The Life and Times of Judge Roy Bean]]'' (1972).\n\nPerkins co-wrote, with composer/lyricist [[Stephen Sondheim]], the screenplay for the film ''[[The Last of Sheila]]'' (1973), for which they received a 1974 [[Edgar Award]] from the [[Mystery Writers of America]] for Best Motion Picture Screenplay.\n\nPerkins was one of the many stars featured in ''[[Murder on the Orient Express (1974 film)|Murder on the Orient Express]]'' (1974). He co-starred with [[Beau Bridges]] in ''[[Lovin' Molly]]'' (also 1974).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ultimatemovierankings.com/anthony-perkins-movies/|title=Anthony Perkins Movies {{!}} Ultimate Movie Rankings|website=www.ultimatemovierankings.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-27}}</ref> He enjoyed success on Broadway in [[Peter Shaffer]]'s 1974 play ''[[Equus (play)|Equus]]'' (where he was a replacement in the leading role originally played by [[Anthony Hopkins]]).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/07/17/archives/stage-perkins-in-equus-shaffer-drama-is-still-magnificent-theater.html|title=Stage: Perkins in 'Equus'|last=Barnes|first=Clive|date=1975-07-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-10-26|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[Off-Broadway]] he directed ''The Wager'' (1974).\n\nPerkins supported [[Diana Ross]] in ''[[Mahogany (film)|Mahogany]]'' (1975) and hosted television's ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' in 1976.\n\nHe co-starred with [[Geraldine Chaplin]] in ''[[Remember My Name]]'' (1978) and had some good roles on TV, playing [[Mary Tyler Moore]]'s husband in ''[[First, You Cry]]'' (1978) and as Javert in ''[[Les Mis\u00e9rables (1978 film)|Les Mis\u00e9rables]]'' (1978). He was featured in [[Walt Disney]]'s ''[[The Black Hole]]'', in 1979. He had another Broadway success with [[Bernard Slade]]'s 1979 play ''[[Romantic Comedy (play)|Romantic Comedy]]'', which ran for 396 performances.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\nPerkins was a villain in ''[[North Sea Hijack]]'' (1980)<ref>{{Citation|last=McLaglen|first=Andrew V.|title=ffolkes|date=1980-04-18|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0081809/|others=Roger Moore, James Mason, Anthony Perkins|accessdate=2017-10-26}}</ref> and one of many names in ''[[Winter Kills (film)|Winter Kills]]'' (1980). He also starred in the 1980 Canadian film ''[[Deadly Companion]]'' (also known as ''Double Negative'').<ref>{{Citation|last=Bloomfield|first=George|title=Double Negative|date=1981-11-30|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0080656/|others=Michael Sarrazin, Susan Clark, Anthony Perkins|accessdate=2017-10-26}}</ref>\n\n===Last roles===\n[[File:Anthony Perkins (1983).jpg|thumb|right|Perkins in 1983]]\nPerkins reprised the role of Norman Bates in ''Psycho'''s three sequels. The first, ''[[Psycho II (film)|Psycho II]]'' (1983), was a box-office success twenty-three years after the original film.\n\nHe went to Australia to appear in ''[[For the Term of His Natural Life (miniseries)|For the Term of His Natural Life]]'' (1983).\n\nAfter ''[[The Glory Boys]]'' (1984) for British television, Perkins made ''[[Crimes of Passion (1984 film)|Crimes of Passion]]'' (1984) for [[Ken Russell]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/person/150440%7C14386/Anthony-Perkins/biography.html|title=Biography for Anthony Perkins|website=Turner Classic Movies|access-date=2017-10-26}}</ref>\n\nHe then starred in and directed ''[[Psycho III]]'' (1986), for which he was nominated for a [[Saturn Award]] for Best Actor.\n\nPerkins had supporting roles in ''[[Napoleon and Josephine: A Love Story]]'' (1987), and ''[[Destroyer (1988 film)|Destroyer]]'' (1988). He directed but did not appear in ''[[Lucky Stiff (film)|Lucky Stiff]]'' (1988).\n\nPerkins starred in some additional horror films, ''[[Edge of Sanity (film)|Edge of Sanity]]'' (1989), ''[[Daughter of Darkness (1990 film)|Daughter of Darkness]]'' (1990), and ''[[I'm Dangerous Tonight]]'' (1990). He played Norman Bates again in the made-for-cable film ''[[Psycho IV: The Beginning]]'' (1990), over which he had much creative control, although he was turned down for director.\n\nPerkins has a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]], an honor he received for his influential and exceptional contributions to the motion\u2013picture industry. It is located at 6801 Hollywood Boulevard in [[Los Angeles]].\n\nIn 1991, Perkins was honored with the Donostia Lifetime Achievement Award at the [[San Sebasti\u00e1n International Film Festival]].\n\nAlthough he was suffering from [[AIDS]], he appeared in eight television productions between 1990 and 1992, including ''[[Daughter of Darkness (1990 film)|Daughter of Darkness]]'' (1990) and ''The Naked Target'' (1992). He made his final appearance in ''[[In the Deep Woods]]'' (1992) with [[Rosanna Arquette]]. He had agreed to provide the voice for the role of the dentist, Dr. Wolfe, in ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode \"[[Last Exit to Springfield]]\" but died before the part could be recorded. In the end, the character was voiced by ''Simpsons'' regular [[Hank Azaria]].<ref name=\"Jean\">{{cite video|people=Jean, Al|date=2004|title=The Simpsons season 4 DVD commentary for the episode \"Last Exit to Springfield\"| medium=DVD|publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref>\n\nPerkins was portrayed by British actor [[James D'Arcy]] in the 2012 biographical drama ''[[Hitchcock (film)|Hitchcock]]'', which starred [[Anthony Hopkins]] as [[Alfred Hitchcock]] and [[Helen Mirren]] as [[Alma Reville]].\n\n==Personal life==\nPerkins was an extremely shy person, especially in the company of women.<ref name=People>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20085251,00.html|title=Return of Psycho|magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]]|first=Brad|last=Darrach|volume=19|issue=23|date=June 13, 1983|accessdate=January 3, 2009}}</ref> According to the posthumous biography ''Split Image'' by Charles Winecoff, he had exclusively [[same-sex relationships]] until his late 30s, including with actor [[Tab Hunter]]; artist [[Christopher Makos]]; dancer [[Rudolf Nureyev]]; composer/lyricist [[Stephen Sondheim]]; and dancer-choreographer [[Grover Dale]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Winecoff|first=Charles|title=Split Image: The Life of Anthony Perkins|location=New York City|publisher=Dutton|date=1996|isbn=0-525-94064-2|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/splitimagelifeof00winerich}}</ref> Perkins has been described as one of the two great men in the life of French songwriter {{ill|Patrick Loiseau|fr}}.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.closermag.fr/article/la-mst-de-dave-son-compagnon-raconte-78352|title=La MST de Dave: son compagnon raconte\u2026|language=fr|magazine=[[Closer (magazine)|Closer]]|date=May 2, 2012|accessdate=November 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPerkins reportedly had his first heterosexual experience at age 39 with actress [[Victoria Principal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20119696,00.html |title=Great Factoids |magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]] |volume=19|issue=23 |date=March 6, 1989 |accessdate=March 24, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150920012637/http://www.people.com/people/article/0%2C%2C20119696%2C00.html |archivedate=September 20, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kennedy|first=Dana|title=Split Image: The Life of Anthony Perkins|url=https://ew.com/article/1996/09/20/split-image-life-anthony-perkins/amp|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=February 5, 2017|date=September 20, 1996}}</ref> \non location filming ''[[The Life and Times of Judge Roy Bean]]'' in 1971.<ref name=People/> He met photographer [[Berry Berenson|Berinthia \"Berry\" Berenson]], the younger sister of actress and model [[Marisa Berenson]], at a party in New York City in 1972.<ref name=People/> They married when he was aged 41 and she was 25, on August 9, 1973 and had two sons: actor [[Oz Perkins]] (b. February 2, 1974), and musician [[Elvis Perkins]] (b. February 9, 1976).<ref name=\"obituary\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2001/sep/14/guardianobituaries.september11|title=Berry Berenson|work=[[The Guardian]]|first=Amanda|last=Hopkinson|date=September 14, 2001|accessdate=August 28, 2009}}</ref> Perkins and Berenson remained married until his death.  In 2001, on the day before the ninth anniversary of his death, she died at age 53 in the [[September 11 attacks]] aboard [[American Airlines Flight 11]]. She was returning to her [[California]] home following a holiday on [[Cape Cod]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Amanda|last=Hopkinson|date=September 14, 2001|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2001/sep/14/guardianobituaries.september11|title=Berry Berenson|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|location=London, England}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nDiagnosed with [[HIV]] during the filming of ''[[Psycho IV: The Beginning]]'', Perkins died at his Los Angeles home on September 12, 1992, from [[AIDS]]-related<ref>{{cite web|url=http://people.com/archive/one-final-mystery-vol-38-no-13/|title=One Final Mystery|publisher=People|first=Mark|last=Goodman|version=Vol. 38, No. 13|date=September 28, 1992|accessdate=August 22, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/09/16/arts/anthony-perkins-s-wife-tells-of-2-years-of-secrecy.html|title=Anthony Perkins's Wife Tells of 2 Years of Secrecy|work=The New York Times|first=Bernard|last=Weinraub|date=September 16, 1992|accessdate=August 22, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1992-09-13/news/mn-1407_1_anthony-perkins|title=Anthony Perkins, 60, Dies; Star of 'Psycho' Had AIDS|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|first=David|last=Ferrell|date=September 13, 1992|accessdate=August 22, 2013}}</ref> pneumonia at age 60.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/anthony-perkins/bio/140397|title=Anthony Perkins|publisher=[[TV Guide]]|accessdate=August 22, 2013}}</ref> His urn, inscribed \"Don't Fence Me In\", is in an altar by a bench on the terrace of his former home in the Hollywood Hills.<ref>Wilson, Scott. ''Resting Places: The Burial Sites of More Than 14,000 Famous Persons'', 3d ed.: 2 (Kindle Locations 36782-36783). McFarland & Company, Inc., Publishers. Kindle Edition.</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1953 || ''[[The Actress]]'' || Fred Whitmarsh ||\n|-\n| 1956 || ''[[Friendly Persuasion (1956 film)|Friendly Persuasion]]'' || Josh Birdwell || [[Golden Globe Award for New Star of the Year \u2013 Actor|Golden Globe Award for Most Promising Newcomer \u2013 Male]]<br />Nominated \u2013 [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]]\n|-\n| 1957 || ''[[Fear Strikes Out]]'' || [[Jimmy Piersall|Jim Piersall]] ||\n|-\n| 1957 || ''[[The Lonely Man]]'' || Riley Wade ||\n|-\n| 1957 || ''[[The Tin Star]]'' || Sheriff Ben Owens ||\n|-\n| 1958 || ''[[This Angry Age]]'' || Joseph Dufresne || Alternate title: ''The Sea Wall''\n|-\n| 1958 || ''[[Desire Under the Elms (film)|Desire Under the Elms]]'' || Eben Cabot ||\n|-\n| 1958 || ''[[The Matchmaker (